subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Branchial crown longer than thorax with 14–16 pairs of radioles. Basal union of the radioles brown colored (
Fig. 22C
). Radioles with four reddish-brown pigmented bands distributed over outer and lateral radiole margins and adjacent pinnules. Outer surfaces of radioles quadrangular basally, rounded distally. Base of the branchial crown with ventral translucent flanges (
Figs 22B–C, F
, 
23B–D
). Sub-distal compound eyes present only in the dorsalmost radiolar pair, spherical covering a short radiolar tip (
Figs 22H
, 
23F
). Other radioles with tips as long as equivalent space of eight pinnules (
Fig. 22I
). Dorsal collar margins diagonal, not fused to faecal groove (
Figs 22A, E
, 
23A, H
). Dorsal lappets absent. Dorsal pockets absent (
Fig. 23A
). Anterior peristomial ring exposed dorsally and laterally above collar (
Figs 22A, E, G
, 
23A–B
). Ventral lappets triangular, not overlapped (
Figs 22B, F
, 
23B–D, G
). Ventral shield of collar rectangular, divided transversally in two parts (
Figs 22B, F
, 
23D, G
). Lateral collar margins not covering bases of radioles (
Fig. 22C
, 
23B
). Dorsal lips purple dorsally, very long (about ¼ of branchial crown length), erect, with mid-rib forming two well developed lateral lamellae (
Fig. 22G
, 
23E, H
). Dorsal pinnular appendages present. Ventral lips small, rounded (
Fig. 23E
). Caruncle long, erect, triangular, placed above mouth, between dorsal lips (
Fig. 23H
). Ventral sacs prominent (
Fig. 23B–C, G
) full of sand in most specimens. Keel absent. Body slender, cylindrical in thorax, flattened in abdomen. Total thorax-abdomen length 23 (37– 38) mm, maximum width 
1 mm
(1.5–1.8) mm throughout most of thorax. Seven thoracic chaetigers. Dorsal thoracic segments brown laterally. Thoracic tori of same length along thorax. Tori in chaetigers 2–3 short, occupying a half of the distance between notopodia and ventral shield margins (
Figs 22C
, 
23B
), not contacting shields. Superior thoracic chaetae elongate, narrowly hooded chaetae (
Fig. 23M–N
); inferior thoracic chaetae 
Type
C (
Figs 23L
,
28E
). Eight thoracic uncini with crest surmounted by 6–8 rows of numerous minute teeth (
Fig. 29E
), handles extending beyond base of shaft of companion chaetae, 2x length of main fang (
Fig. 23I
). Companion chaetae with teardrop and sickle-shaped membranes within same torus (
Fig. 29F
). Abdominal segments 63–83. Abdominal chaetae elongate, narrowly hooded chaetae (
Fig. 23O
); chaetae in posterior row longer than those in anterior row. Abdominal uncini with main fang surmounted by 8–9 rows of numerous minute teeth (
Fig. 23K
). Posterior margin of pygidium triangular (
Fig. 22J–K
) without eyes. Tubes covered with sand grains (
Fig. 22D
).

GAMETES: Females with the abdomen full of oocytes. Posterior abdominal chaetigers with nephridia visible, full with sperm tissue (
Fig. 23O
). Sperm in posterior abdomen with a rounded nucleus, small acrosome, two rounded mitochondria and a long flagellum (
Fig. 23J
).
